  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the best way to remove permanent marker from a countertop?",
  "response": "Removing permanent marker from a countertop can be challenging, but several methods can be effective, depending on the countertop material. Here are some steps you can try:\n\n### For Laminate, Granite, or Solid Surface Countertops:\n\n1. **Dry Erase Marker Method:**\n   - Write over the permanent marker stain with a dry erase marker.\n   - Wipe the area with a clean, dry cloth. The dry erase ink can help lift the permanent marker.\n\n2. **Alcohol-Based Solutions:**\n   - Dampen a cloth with rubbing alcohol (isopropyl alcohol) or hand sanitizer.\n   - Gently rub the stained area. Be cautious not to scrub too hard, as this might damage some surfaces.\n   - Wipe the area clean with a damp cloth and dry thoroughly.\n\n3. **Toothpaste:**\n   - Apply a small amount of white, non-gel toothpaste to the stain.\n   - Gently rub the area with a soft cloth or an old toothbrush.\n   - Rinse with water and dry thoroughly.\n\n4. **Baking Soda and Water:**\n   - Make a paste using baking soda and water.\n   - Apply the paste to the stain and let it sit for a few minutes.\n   - Scrub gently with a soft cloth or sponge.\n   - Rinse with water and dry thoroughly.\n\n### For Marble or Natural Stone Countertops:\n\n1. **Acetone (Nail Polish Remover):**\n   - Moisten a cloth with acetone.\n   - Gently rub the stained area. Be very careful, as acetone can damage some surfaces.\n   - Rinse thoroughly with water and dry.\n\n2. **Specialized Stone Cleaner:**\n   - Use a cleaner specifically designed for natural stone.\n   - Follow the product instructions carefully.\n\n### General Tips:\n\n- **Test First:** Always test a small, inconspicuous area first to ensure the removal method won\u2019t damage your countertop.\n- **Avoid Abrasives:** Do not use abrasive cleaners or scrubbers, as they can scratch the surface.\n- **Professional Help:** If the stain persists, consider consulting a professional cleaner, especially for high-end or sensitive materials.\n\nRemember, the effectiveness of these methods can vary based on the type of countertop and the extent of the stain. Be patient and persistent, and you may need to try a combination of methods to completely remove the permanent marker.",
